In [logic](/Logic), an **infinite-valued logic**, also known as **real-valued logic** or **infinitely-many-valued logic**, is a departure from the traditional, binary understanding of truth. It's a [many-valued logic](/Many-valued_logic) where the spectrum of [truth values](/Truth_values) isn't confined to a simple "true" or "false." Instead, it encompasses a [continuous](/Continuous_or_discrete_variable) range, much like the real numbers themselves. This concept stands in stark contrast to the classical Aristotelian view, where the [law of the excluded middle](/Law_of_the_excluded_middle) dictated that a proposition must be either true or false, leaving no room for ambiguity or intermediate states.

Modern logic, however, has explored beyond this binary constraint. [Three-valued logic](/Three-valued_logic), for instance, introduces a third possibility, often interpreted as "undecided" or "unknown." This is a form of [finite-valued logic](/Finite-valued_logic), where the truth values are discrete and countable. Infinite-valued logic, on the other hand, embraces a more fluid, continuous landscape. This is where [fuzzy logic](/Fuzzy_logic) finds its home, though it's worth noting that fuzzy logic, in its various manifestations, can also incorporate finite-valued systems. For example, finite-valued logic has found applications in [Boolean-valued modeling](/Boolean-valued_model), [description logics](/Description_logic), and even in the [defuzzification](/Defuzzification) processes that are integral to many fuzzy logic systems.

### History

The journey towards understanding continuous truth values is as old as the concepts of infinity and infinitesimals themselves. [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton) and [Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz), in their groundbreaking work on differential and integral [calculus](/Calculus) in the late 17th century, grappled with both infinities and [infinitesimals](/Infinitesimals). Later, in the 19th century, [Richard Dedekind](/Richard_Dedekind), in his elegant definition of [real numbers](/Real_number) through [certain sets](/Construction_of_the_real_numbers) of [rational numbers](/Rational_number), also posited an axiom of [continuity](/Law_of_continuity). This axiom asserted the existence of a single, precise value at the limit of any process of [trial and error](/Trial_and_error) [approximation](/Approximation). This insistence on a definitive point within a continuous flow is a precursor to the ideas explored in infinite-valued logic.

The 20th century saw more direct formalizations. [Jan Łukasiewicz](/Jan_%C5%81ukasiewicz) pioneered the development of many-valued logics, first introducing a system of three-valued logic in 1920. He subsequently expanded this to generalized many-valued logics in 1922, eventually developing [logics](/%C5%81ukasiewicz_logic) that could accommodate an infinite number of truth values, specifically those represented by the [aleph-null](/Aleph_number) symbol, &#x2135;<sub>0</sub>, signifying an infinite quantity within a defined range.

Around the same time, [Kurt Gödel](/Kurt_G%C3%B6del) was making profound contributions to mathematical logic. He developed a [deductive system](/G%C3%B6del_logic) applicable to both finite- and infinite-valued [first-order logic](/First-order_logic)—a logic where a [predicate](/Predicate_(mathematical_logic)) could relate to a single [subject](/Proposition). Gödel also explored [intermediate logic](/Intermediate_logic), a form of [intuitionistic logic](/Intuitionistic_logic) useful for proofs like [consistency proofs](/Dialectica_interpretation) for [arithmetic](/Arithmetic). In 1932, Gödel demonstrated a crucial insight: [logical intuition](/Logical_intuition), the seemingly innate human capacity to grasp logical truths, could not be fully captured by [finite-valued logic](/Finite-valued_logic) alone. This suggested that a richer, perhaps infinite, structure was at play.

The possibility of extending truth values beyond the 0-to-1 range of real numbers also emerged. What if truth values could be represented by [complex numbers](/Complex_number), incorporating an [imaginary](/Imaginary_number) dimension? Such multidimensional truth values, perhaps ranging from 0 to *i*, could offer new avenues for systems of [paraconsistent logic](/Paraconsistent_logic), which are designed to handle contradictions. This conceptual leap could lead to the independent development of [multidimensional](/Multidimensional_system) infinite-valued logic, distinct from its real-valued counterpart.

The modern era of fuzzy logic owes much to [Lotfi A. Zadeh](/Lotfi_A._Zadeh), who proposed a formal methodology for [fuzzy logic](/Fuzzy_logic) and its applications in the early 1970s. By 1973, researchers were already applying Zadeh's fuzzy controller theory to practical problems in mechanical and industrial engineering. This evolved into the concept of fuzzy modeling, which was later integrated with [neural networks](/Neural_network) in the 1980s and [machine learning](/Machine_learning) in the 1990s. Zadeh's work also spurred generalizations within the family of [t-norm fuzzy logics](/T-norm_fuzzy_logics).

### Examples

The foundation of basic [fuzzy logic](/Fuzzy_logic) lies in [continuous](/Continuous_or_discrete_variable) [t-norms](/T-norm), which are [binary operations](/Binary_operation) defined on the real unit interval [0, 1]. This seemingly abstract concept has found its way into a surprising array of real-world applications. You'll encounter fuzzy logic in [facial recognition systems](/Facial_recognition_system), the smarts behind [home appliances](/Home_appliance), the precise control in [anti-lock braking systems](/Anti-lock_braking_system) and [automatic transmissions](/Automatic_transmission), and the smooth operation of controllers for [rapid transit](/Rapid_transit) systems and [unmanned aerial vehicles](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle). It's also a cornerstone in [knowledge-based](/Knowledge-based) systems, [engineering optimization](/Engineering_optimization), [weather forecasting](/Weather_forecasting), [pricing](/Pricing) strategies, and [risk assessment](/Risk_assessment) [modeling systems](/Systems_modeling). Even in [medical diagnosis](/Medical_diagnosis) and treatment planning, and in the complex world of international [trading](/Trade), fuzzy logic plays a role.

More specifically, fuzzy logic is employed to fine-tune efficiency in [thermostats](/Thermostat) for optimal heating and cooling. It's crucial for industrial [automation](/Automation) and [process control](/Process_control), adding a layer of intelligent adaptability. In the realm of digital media, it contributes to [computer animation](/Computer_animation), [signal processing](/Signal_processing), and sophisticated [data analysis](/Data_analysis). The impact of fuzzy logic on [machine learning](/Machine_learning) and [data mining](/Data_mining) has been particularly significant, offering new ways to extract meaningful patterns from vast datasets.

In the context of [infinitary logic](/Infinitary_logic), infinite-valued logic provides a framework for expressing degrees of provability for propositions. This is often visualized through evaluated formulas, presented as ordered pairs where each pair consists of a truth degree symbol and the corresponding formula.

Within [mathematics](/Mathematics) itself, infinite-valued logic offers a way to express abstract concepts without relying on specific numbers. This "number-free semantics" allows for the derivation of facts about classical mathematical notions through logical deduction. [T-norm fuzzy logics](/T-norm_fuzzy_logic) are particularly adept at this, enabling the elimination of explicit references to real numbers in definitions and theorems. This simplification can make certain mathematical concepts more accessible and facilitate broader generalizations. A framework for this number-free formalization of mathematical ideas is known as fuzzy class theory.

Philosophical quandaries, such as the notorious [Sorites paradox](/Sorites_paradox), have also found fertile ground for exploration within infinite-valued logic, particularly in systems like fuzzy [epistemicism](/Epistemicism). The Sorites paradox, which questions how a heap of sand can be formed from individual grains, hinges on the idea that adding a single grain cannot transform something that isn't a heap into one. The stepwise progression, where truth is gradually "leaked" rather than abruptly changing, offers a compelling counter-argument within the continuous framework of infinite-valued logic.

Perhaps most profoundly, infinite-valued logic has served as an invaluable tool for understanding the very nature of human [logical intuition](/Logical_intuition). As mentioned, [Kurt Gödel](/Kurt_G%C3%B6del) himself initially attempted to explain this faculty through finite-valued logic before concluding that its basis lay in the richer, infinite domain. Despite these advances, open questions persist regarding how to adequately represent indeterminate truth values within the semantics of [natural language](/Natural_language). The subtle shades of meaning, the inherent ambiguity, and the fluid nature of human communication are not always easily captured by discrete logical systems.